[32m│[0m ```bash                                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:32784/edit_profile/2 \                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m   -H "Cookie: access_token=\"Bearer                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiIxIiwiZXhwIjoxNzY3NDAzMDcwfQ. [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Fw2cG_OJCIhKYOVM9A1XwePzsSNW8eYbkq0AW7TZf2w\"" \                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m   -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m   -d "name=hacked&is_admin=1"                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **confidence_score:** 0.95                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **thoughts:**                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This is a textbook IDOR vulnerability. The application has inconsistent      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m authorization checks:                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - GET endpoints properly validate that the JWT token's `sub` claim matches   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the company_id in the URL                                                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - POST endpoint to `/edit_profile/{company_id}` fails to perform this        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m validation, allowing any authenticated user to modify any company's profile  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The vulnerability is particularly severe because:                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. It allows horizontal privilege escalation (accessing/modifying other      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m users' data)                                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. The `is_admin` field can be manipulated, potentially leading to vertical  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m privilege escalation                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. The admin status field is NOT disabled in the form response after         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m exploitation, suggesting backend validation is also missing                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Root cause: Missing authorization check in the POST handler - it             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m authenticates the user but doesn't verify they own the resource being        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m modified. The GET handlers correctly implement this check.                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Recommendation: Add authorization validation to verify `current_user.id ==   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m company_id` in the POST `/edit_profile/{company_id}` endpoint.               [32m│[0m
